Duplicate and Missing Cases

lindbrook

2016-09-25

Overview

John Snowâ€™s map of the 1854 cholera outbreak in London is a canonical example of data visualization:1

In 1992, Rusty Dodson and Waldo Tobler digitized the map. While the original data are no longer available,2 they are preserved in Michael Friendlyâ€™s HistData R package. Those data are plotted below:

However, there are two apparent coding errors, which stem from three misplaced cases.

While the data record 578 bars, only 575 of them have a unique x-y coordinate.3 Three pairs have identical coordinates: 1) 93 and 214; 2) 91 and 241; and 3) 209 and 429. Within the scheme of stacking bars to represent the fatality count, this cannot occur. All bars should have a unique x-y coordinate. For this reason, duplicates are likely to be coding errors.

duplicates <- Snow.deaths[(duplicated(Snow.deaths[, c("x", "y")])), ]

duplicates.id <- lapply(duplicates$x, function(i) {
  Snow.deaths[Snow.deaths$x == i, "case"]
})

Snow.deaths[unlist(duplicates.id), ]
#>     case        x        y
#> 93    93 12.84460 11.61027
#> 214  214 12.84460 11.61027
#> 91    91 12.65285 11.26382
#> 241  241 12.65285 11.26382
#> 209  209 12.68321 11.28437
#> 429  429 12.68321 11.28437

Fortunately, a careful comparison of Snowâ€™s map and the map generated by Dodson and Toblerâ€™s data reveals that there are three â€œmissingâ€ bars in the latter. An expedient â€œfixâ€ would be to use the duplicate observations to fill in for the â€œmissingâ€ bars:

fatalities <- Snow.deaths

fix <- data.frame(x = c(12.56974, 12.53617, 12.33145), y = c(11.51226, 11.58107, 14.80316))

fatalities[c(91, 93, 209), c("x", "y")] <- fix

This fixed data set is available as fatalities in the package and as Snow.deaths2 in Michael Friendlyâ€™s package (>= ver. 0.7-8). For those interested, an explanation of how I arrived at the values follows.

A Solution

One solution to these problems is to use the three duplicate observations from Cambridge Street to fill in for the three â€œmissingâ€ observations on Broad and Noel Streets. This is both plausible and reasonable.

What makes this plausible is that with the exception of the x-y coordinate of the case at the base of stack, the remaining coordinates, which make up 44% (257/578) of all bars and which include the proposed locations for the three â€œmissingâ€ observations, do not represent the location of a case. They only serve to align bars within a stack. For this reason, putting aside concerns about alignment or the number of bars, there should be no objections about moving this class of bars.

What makes this reasonable is that I do not relocate bars by hand. Instead, I use geometric interpolation. The basic idea is straightforward: use existing observations in a stack to determine the â€œstandardâ€ unit distance between bars; then use multiples of the unit distance to position â€œmissingâ€ observations.

As an example, consider 40 Broad Street. On Snowâ€™s map, there are four cases but in Dodson and Tobler there are just two. Visual inspection leads me to make three claims: 1) the distance between the two observed cases, 32 and 122, is greater than neighboring sites; 2) there appears to be room for just one â€œmissingâ€ case between 32 and 122; and 3) the other â€œmissingâ€ case should be located just beyond case 122. The proposed coordinates are illustrated below:

Geometric interpolation: unit distance

To explain how I got these coordinates, I first focus on the computation of the unit distance in one dimension and then I will move to the general two dimensional case. Again, I use 40 Broad Street as the example.

To illustrate the computation the unit distance, I simplify things by rotating the data so that the stack lies in a single dimension (horizontal). Thus, to implement my claim that only one â€œmissingâ€ case fits between cases 32 and 122 I set the unit distance between the two observed cases to 2:

I then place one â€œmissingâ€ case 1 unit away from 32:

And place the other â€œmissingâ€ case three units away:

Geometric interpolation: in 2 dimensions

Because stacks typically lie in two dimensional space and because we need to respect features like roads and addresses, the actual interpolation is a bit more complicated than the above suggests.

Consider the example of the â€œmissingâ€ observation that lies between cases 32 and 122. Just as with the one dimensional example above, the â€œmissingâ€ observation should be located one unit away from case 32. The difference in two dimensions is that it needs to be located one unit away from case 32 (at the red â€œxâ€) as measured along the line that runs through the stackâ€™s axis (black dotted line).

To compute the coordinates for the â€œmissingâ€ case, I use geometry to find the points of intersection between a circle and line. The circle is simple: its center is the reference point (case 32), and its radius is the desired multiple of the unit distance, which is 1 in this example. The line is more complicated: it is the line that runs through the stackâ€™s central axis.

What makes the line complicated is that, essentially, none of the bars in any of the stacks in Dodson and Tobler are perfectly aligned. To ensure that there is only one unique axis for any stack, I impose two constraints: 1) a stack must lie along an axis that is orthogonal to the road (segment) where the stack is located4; and 2) the axis must pass through the reference point, the bar at the base of the stack (the bar closest to the stackâ€™s home road segment).

As a consequence, the line drawn through the stackâ€™s axis will pass through the circleâ€™s center, which is also the reference point:

This means that there will always be two points of intersection (red squares):

Thus, finding the coordinates of the â€œmissingâ€ observations boils down to solving a quadratic equation. I do so using the formulas below:

# Equation of line for the "home" road segment
# "segment" is the numeric ID of one of the 528 sets of line segments in Dodson and Tobler
segmentOLS <- function(segment) {
  lm(y ~ x, data = street.list[[segment]])
}

# Slope for orthogonal stack axis
orthogonalSlope <- function(segment) {
  ols <- segmentOLS(segment)
  -1 / coef(ols)[2]
}

# Intercept for orthogonal stack axis
# "case" if the reference point of a stack
orthogonalIntercept <- function(case, segment) {
  Snow.deaths[case, "y"] - orthogonalSlope(segment) * Snow.deaths[case, "x"]
}

# unit distance is a function of the Euclidean distance between "case1" and "case2"
unitDistance <- function(case1, case2) {
  dist(Snow.deaths[c(case1, case2), c("x", "y")])
}

# Quadratic equation
quadratic <- function(a, b, c) {
  root1 <- (-b + sqrt(b^2 - 4 * a * c)) / (2 * a)
  root2 <- (-b - sqrt(b^2 - 4 * a * c)) / (2 * a)
  c(root1, root2)
}

# Geometric interpolation
# "multiplier" scales and defines the unit distance
interpolatedPoints <- function(case1, case2, multiplier = 0.5, segment) {
  p <- Snow.deaths[case1, "x"]
  q <- Snow.deaths[case1, "y"]
  radius <- multiplier * unitDistance(case1, case2)
  m <- orthogonalSlope(segment)
  b <- orthogonalIntercept(case1)
  A <- (m^2 + 1)
  B <- 2 * (m * b - m * q - p)
  C <- (q^2 - radius^2 + p^2 - 2 * b * q + b^2)
  quadratic(A, B, C)
}
